------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Requirements                                                         -
------------------------------------------------------------------------

CPython version 2.6 or 2.7 (Not 3.x ready yet.)

PyPy version 1.4.1 or higher (simulations will run 2x as fast)

IPython (used for analysis shell)

Python Packages:
argparse (if using python 2.6)
discover (if you want to run all the tests at once)
yaml

------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Setup                                                                -
------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Before you bother running any simulations, I highly recommend that
you perform all the unit tests:

./run_tests.sh

    If they do not all pass, you should make sure that all required packages
are installed, then start hunting for the problem.  If you need help getting
the software to run, please check the project's Google Code site (especially
the wiki).

    If you have found a portability issue or other bug, please submit a ticket
on the project's Google Code site.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Running                                                              -
------------------------------------------------------------------------
    To perform a simulation, create a new directory (probably in the
data directory) and place parameters and object graph configuration
files in that directory:

mkdir results/new_simulation
cp examples/pollard_2002/*.yaml results/new_simulation/

    Run the simulations, specifying the number of simulations to run
per parameter set:

./sim.sh -d results/new_simulation -n 8

    To analyze the data, stay in the same directory and use console.py:

./console.py

    Once in the console, you can combine the simulation results using:

ac = io.load_directory('results/new_simulation')

    Now you can perform a variety of available analysis.  Check the
actin_dynamics/analysis and actin_dynamics/visualization modules for
more info.  One example would be:

analysis.perform_pollard(ac)
visualization.pollard.plot_fit(ac)

